# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gcp-bigtable
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gcp-bigtable/apache-hbase] HBase features compression, in-memory operation, and Bloom filters on a per-column basis as outlined in the original Bigtable paper.
[src:gcp-bigtable/apache-hbase] Tables in HBase can serve as the input and output for MapReduce jobs run in Hadoop, and may be accessed through the Java API but also through REST, Avro or Thrift gateway APIs.
[src:gcp-bigtable/apache-hbase] HBase is a wide-column store and has been widely adopted because of its lineage with Hadoop and HDFS.
[src:gcp-bigtable/apache-hbase] HBase runs on top of HDFS and is well-suited for fast read and write operations on large datasets with high throughput and low input/output latency.
[src:gcp-bigtable/apache-hbase] HBase is not a direct replacement for a classic SQL database, however Apache Phoenix project provides a SQL layer for HBase as well as JDBC driver that can be integrated with various analytics and business intelligence applications.
[src:gcp-bigtable/apache-hbase] The Apache Trafodion project provides a SQL query engine with ODBC and JDBC drivers and distributed ACID transaction protection across multiple statements, tables and rows that use HBase as a storage engine.
[src:gcp-bigtable/apache-hbase] HBase is now serving several data-driven websites but Facebook's Messaging Platform migrated from HBase to MyRocks in 2018.
[src:gcp-bigtable/apache-hbase] Unlike relational and traditional databases, HBase does not support SQL scripting; instead the equivalent is written in Java, employing similarity with a MapReduce application.
[src:gcp-bigtable/apache-hbase] In the parlance of Eric Brewer's CAP Theorem, HBase is a CP type system.
[src:gcp-bigtable/apache-hbase] Apache HBase began as a project by the company Powerset out of a need to process massive amounts of data for the purposes of natural-language search.
[src:gcp-bigtable/apache-hbase] Since 2010 it is a top-level Apache project.
[src:gcp-bigtable/apache-hbase] Facebook elected to implement its new messaging platform using HBase in November 2010, but migrated away from HBase in 2018.
[src:gcp-bigtable/apache-hbase] The 2.5.x series is the current stable release line, it supersedes earlier release lines.
[src:gcp-bigtable/bigtable] It is now used by a number of Google applications, such as Google Analytics, web indexing, MapReduce, which is often used for generating and modifying data stored in Bigtable, Google Maps, Google Books search, "My Search History", Google Earth, Blogger.com, Google Code hosting, YouTube, and Gmail.
[src:gcp-bigtable/bigtable] Google's reasons for developing its own database include scalability and better control of performance characteristics.
[src:gcp-bigtable/bigtable] Apache HBase and Cassandra are some of the best known open source projects that were modeled after Bigtable.
[src:gcp-bigtable/bigtable] Bigtable offers HBase and Cassandra compatible APIs.
[src:gcp-bigtable/bigtable] On 6 May 2015, a public version of Bigtable was made available as a part of Google Cloud under the name Cloud Bigtable.
[src:gcp-bigtable/bigtable] As of April 2024, Bigtable manages over 10 Exabytes of data and serves more than 7 billion requests per second.
[src:gcp-bigtable/bigtable] Since its launch, Google announced a number of updates to Bigtable, including SQL support, incremental materialized views, global secondary indexes and automated scalability.
[src:gcp-bigtable/bigtable] Bigtable is one of the prototypical examples of a wide-column store.
[src:gcp-bigtable/bigtable] It maps two arbitrary string values (row key and column key) and timestamp (hence three-dimensional mapping) into an associated arbitrary byte array.
[src:gcp-bigtable/bigtable] It is not a relational database and can be better defined as a sparse, distributed multi-dimensional sorted map.
[src:gcp-bigtable/bigtable] It is built on Colossus (Google File System), Chubby Lock Service, SSTable (log-structured storage like LevelDB) and a few other Google technologies.
[src:gcp-bigtable/bigtable] Bigtable is designed to scale into the petabyte range across "hundreds or thousands of machines, and to make it easy to add more machines [to] the system and automatically start taking advantage of those resources without any reconfiguration".
[src:gcp-bigtable/bigtable] For example, Google's copy of the web can be stored in a bigtable where the row key is a domain-reversed URL, and columns describe various properties of a web page, with one particular column holding the page itself.
[src:gcp-bigtable/bigtable] The page column can have several timestamped versions describing different copies of the web page timestamped by when they were fetched.
[src:gcp-bigtable/bigtable] Each cell of a bigtable can have zero or more timestamped versions of the data.
[src:gcp-bigtable/bigtable] Another function of the timestamp is to allow for both versioning and garbage collection of expired data.
[src:gcp-bigtable/bigtable] Tables are split into multiple *tablets* – segments of the table are split at certain row keys so that each tablet is a few hundred megabytes or a few gigabytes in size.
[src:gcp-bigtable/bigtable] A bigtable is somewhat like a mapreduce worker pool in that thousands to hundreds of thousands of tablet shards may be served by hundreds to thousands of BigTable servers.
[src:gcp-bigtable/bigtable] When Table size threaten to grow beyond a specified limit, the tablets may be compressed using the algorithm BMDiff and the Zippy compression algorithm publicly known and open-sourced as Snappy, which is a less space-optimal variation of LZ77 but more efficient in terms of computing time.
[src:gcp-bigtable/bigtable] The locations in the GFS of tablets are recorded as database entries in multiple special tablets, which are called "META1" tablets.
[src:gcp-bigtable/bigtable] META1 tablets are found by querying the single "META0" tablet, which typically resides on a server of its own since it is often queried by clients as to the location of the "META1" tablet which itself has the answer to the question of where the actual data is located.
[src:gcp-bigtable/bigtable] Like GFS's master server, the META0 server is not generally a bottleneck since the processor time and bandwidth necessary to discover and transmit META1 locations is minimal and clients aggressively cache locations to minimize queries.
[src:gcp-bigtable/key-value-database] A **key-value database**, or **key-value store**, is a data storage paradigm designed for storing, retrieving, and managing associative arrays, a data structure more commonly known today as a *dictionary*.
[src:gcp-bigtable/key-value-database] Dictionaries contain a collection of *objects*, or *records*, which in turn have many different *fields* within them.
[src:gcp-bigtable/key-value-database] These records are stored and retrieved using a *key* that uniquely identifies the record, and is used to find the data within the database.
[src:gcp-bigtable/key-value-database] Key-value databases differ from the better known relational databases (RDB).
[src:gcp-bigtable/key-value-database] RDBs pre-define the data structure in the database as a series of tables containing fields with well-defined data types.
[src:gcp-bigtable/key-value-database] Exposing the data types to the database program allows it to apply various optimizations.
[src:gcp-bigtable/key-value-database] In contrast, key-value systems treat the value as opaque to the database itself, and typically support only simple operations such as storing, retrieving, updating, and deleting a value by its key.
[src:gcp-bigtable/key-value-database] This offers considerable flexibility and makes such systems well suited to low-latency, high-throughput workloads dominated by direct key lookups, but less suitable for applications that require complex queries or explicit relationships among records.
[src:gcp-bigtable/key-value-database] A lack of standardization, limited transaction support, and relatively simple query interfaces long restricted many key-value systems to specialized uses, but the rapid move to cloud computing after 2010 helped drive renewed interest in them as part of the broader NoSQL movement.
[src:gcp-bigtable/key-value-database] Some graph databases, such as ArangoDB, are also key–value databases internally, adding the concept of relationships (*pointers*) between records as a first-class data type.
[src:gcp-bigtable/key-value-database] Key–value systems span a wide consistency spectrum, from eventually consistent designs to strongly consistent or serializable ones, and some allow the consistency level to be configured as part of the trade-off against latency and availability.
[src:gcp-bigtable/key-value-database] Renewed interest in key–value and other NoSQL systems was driven in part by the demands of big data, distributed, and cloud applications.
[src:gcp-bigtable/key-value-database] Their scalability and availability made them attractive for cloud data management, although limited transaction support, low-level query interfaces, and the lack of standardization remained obstacles to wider adoption.
[src:gcp-bigtable/key-value-database] Some maintain data in memory (RAM), while others employ solid-state drives or rotating disks.
[src:gcp-bigtable/key-value-database] Some key–value systems add additional structure to their keys.
[src:gcp-bigtable/key-value-database] For example, Oracle NoSQL Database organizes records using composite keys with "major" and "minor" components, an arrangement that Oracle compares to a directory-path structure in a file system.
[src:gcp-bigtable/key-value-database] More generally, however, key–value stores are defined by their use of unique keys associated with opaque values and by their emphasis on simple key-based operations.
[src:gcp-bigtable/key-value-database] Unix included *dbm* (database manager), a minimal database library written by Ken Thompson for managing associative arrays with a single key and hash-based access.
[src:gcp-bigtable/key-value-database] Later implementations and related libraries included sdbm, GNU dbm (gdbm), and Berkeley DB.
[src:gcp-bigtable/key-value-database] A more recent example is RocksDB, a persistent key–value storage engine developed at Facebook and designed for large-scale applications.
[src:gcp-bigtable/key-value-database] Other examples include in-memory systems such as Memcached and Redis, and persistent systems such as Berkeley DB, Riak, and Voldemort.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] In computer science, the **log-structured merge-tree** (also known as **LSM tree**, or **LSMT**) is a data structure with performance characteristics that make it attractive for providing indexed access to files with high insert volume, such as transactional log data.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] LSM trees, like other search trees, maintain key-value pairs.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] LSM trees maintain data in two or more separate structures, each of which is optimized for its respective underlying storage medium; data is synchronized between the two structures efficiently, in batches.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] One simple version of the LSM tree is a two-level LSM tree.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] As described by Patrick O'Neil, a two-level LSM tree comprises two tree-like structures, called C0 and C1.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] C0 is smaller and entirely resident in memory, whereas C1 is resident on disk.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] New records are inserted into the memory-resident C0 component.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] If the insertion causes the C0 component to exceed a certain size threshold, a contiguous segment of entries is removed from C0 and merged into C1 on disk.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] The performance characteristics of LSM trees stem from the fact that each component is tuned to the characteristics of its underlying storage medium, and that data is efficiently migrated across media in rolling batches, using an algorithm reminiscent of merge sort.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] Such tuning involves writing data in a sequential manner as opposed to as a series of separate random access requests.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] This optimization reduces total seek time in hard-disk drives (HDDs) and latency in solid-state drives (SSDs).
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] Most LSM trees used in practice employ multiple levels.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] Level 0 is kept in main memory, and might be represented using a tree.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] The on-disk data is organized into sorted *runs* of data.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] Each run contains data sorted by the index key.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] A run can be represented on disk as a single file, or alternatively as a collection of files with non-overlapping key ranges.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] To perform a query on a particular key to get its associated value, one must search in the Level 0 tree and also each run.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] The Stepped-Merge version of the LSM tree is a variant of the LSM tree that supports multiple levels with multiple tree structures at each level.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] A particular key may appear in several runs, and what that means for a query depends on the application.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] Some applications simply want the newest key-value pair with a given key.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] Some applications must combine the values in some way to get the proper aggregate value to return.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] For example, in Apache Cassandra, each value represents a row in a database, and different versions of the row may have different sets of columns.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] In order to keep down the cost of queries, the system must avoid a situation where there are too many runs.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] Extensions to the 'leveled' method to incorporate B+ tree structures have been suggested, for example bLSM and Diff-Index.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] LSM-tree was originally designed for write-intensive workloads.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] As increasingly more read and write workloads co-exist under an LSM-tree storage structure, read data accesses can experience high latency and low throughput due to frequent invalidations of cached data in buffer caches by LSM-tree compaction operations.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] To re-enable effective buffer caching for fast data accesses, a Log-Structured buffered-Merged tree (LSbM-tree) is proposed and implemented.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] In LSM-trees, write operations are designed to optimize performance by reducing random I/O and leveraging sequential disk writes.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] When a write operation is initiated, the data is first buffered in an in-memory component, often implemented using a sorted data structure such as a Skip list or B+ tree.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] Once the in-memory buffer becomes full, it is flushed to the disk as an immutable sorted component at the first level (C1).
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] This flush is performed sequentially, ensuring high I/O efficiency by avoiding the costly random writes typical of traditional indexing methods.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] To maintain durability, the system may use a write-ahead log (WAL) that records all incoming writes before they are added to the memory buffer.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] This ensures that no data is lost in the event of a crash during a write.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] As data accumulates across levels on the disk, LSM trees employ a merge process similar to merge sort to consolidate entries and maintain a consistent sorted order across levels.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] This process also handles updates and deletes, removing redundant or obsolete entries.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] Updates are treated as new writes, while deletes are marked with a tombstone entry, which is a placeholder indicating that the key has been deleted.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] These tombstones are later removed during the merging process.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] Two common merging policies govern how data flows through the levels: levelling and tiering.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] In levelling, only one component exists per level, and merging happens more frequently, reducing the total number of components but increasing write amplification.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] In tiering, multiple components can coexist within a level, and merging occurs less frequently, reducing write amplification but increasing read costs because more components need to be searched.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] This design leads to amortized write costs of $O\left({T\cdot L \over B}\right)$ for leveling merge policies, where T is the size ratio between levels, L is the number of levels, and B is the number of entries per page.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] A point lookup operation retrieves the value associated with a specific key.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] In LSM trees, because of the multi-level structure and the immutability of disk components, point lookups involve checking several levels to ensure the most up-to-date value for the key is returned.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] The process begins with a search in the in-memory component (C0), which holds the latest data.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] Since this component is organized as a sorted structure, the search is efficient.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] If the key is found here, its value is returned right away.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] If the key isn't found in memory, the search moves to the disk components, starting with the first level (C1) and continuing through deeper levels (C2, C3, etc.).
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] Each disk level is also sorted, allowing for efficient searches using methods like binary search or tree search.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] Newer levels are checked first because they contain the most recent updates and deletions for the key.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] To make the search faster, LSM trees often use a bloom filter for each on-disk component.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] These filters are probabilistic structures that help quickly determine whether a key is definitely absent from a component.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] Before accessing any disk component, the system checks the Bloom filter.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] If the filter indicates the key is not present, the component is skipped, saving time.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] If the filter suggests the key might be there, the system proceeds to search for the component.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] The lookup operation stops as soon as the key is found, ensuring the most recent version is returned.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] If the search reaches the final level without finding the key, the system concludes that the key doesn't exist.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] Point lookup complexity is $O(L)$ without Bloom filters, as each level must be searched.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] With Bloom filters, the cost for zero-result lookups is significantly reduced to $O\left(L\cdot e^{-{\frac {M}{N}}}\right)$ , where M is the total Bloom filter size and N is the number of keys.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] For existing key lookups, the cost is $O(1)$ due to the presence of Bloom filters.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] A range query retrieves all key-value pairs within a specified range.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] The operation involves scanning multiple components across the LSM tree's hierarchical structure and consolidating entries to ensure accurate and complete results.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] A range query begins by searching the in-memory component (C0).
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] Since this component is typically a sorted data structure, range queries can be done efficiently.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] Once the in-memory component is finished, the query proceeds to the disk components, starting from the first level (C1) and continuing to deeper levels.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] Each disk component is also stored as a sorted structure allowing efficient range scans within individual components.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] To perform the range query, the system locates the starting point in each relevant component and scans sequentially until the end of the range is reached.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] The results from each component are then merged into a priority queue to reconcile duplicates, updates, and deletes, ensuring the final result only includes the latest version of each key.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] For efficiency, LSM trees often divide disk components into smaller, disjoint key ranges.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] In this way, when processing a range query, the system can search only the partitions that have overlap ranges to reduce the number of components accessed.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] Similar to point lookup, Bloom filters are sometimes used to quickly decide whether a disk component contains any keys within the queried range, allowing the system to skip components that are guaranteed to be irrelevant.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] The performance of a range query in LSM-trees depends on the query's selectivity.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] For short-range queries, which access fewer keys than twice the number of levels, the query must examine components across all levels, leading to a cost proportional to the number of levels.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] For long-range queries, which access many keys, the price is dominated by scanning the largest level, as it contains most of the data.
[src:gcp-bigtable/log-structured-merge-tree] For this reason, the runtime for short-range queries is $O(L)$ and $O\left({\frac {s}{B}}\right)$ for long-range queries, where s is the number of keys in the range.
[src:gcp-bigtable/sharding] A **database shard**, or simply a **shard**, is a horizontal partition of data within a database or search engine.
[src:gcp-bigtable/sharding] Each shard may be held on a separate database server instance in order to spread across multiple servers.
[src:gcp-bigtable/sharding] Some data in a database may remain present in all shards, while other data is stored in only one shard.
[src:gcp-bigtable/sharding] In such cases, each shard acts as the single source for its subset of data.
[src:gcp-bigtable/sharding] There are numerous advantages to the horizontal partitioning of data.
[src:gcp-bigtable/sharding] Since tables are divided and distributed into multiple servers, the total number of rows in each table in each database is reduced.
[src:gcp-bigtable/sharding] This reduces index size, which generally improves search performance.
[src:gcp-bigtable/sharding] A database shard can be placed on separate hardware, and multiple shards can be placed on multiple machines.
[src:gcp-bigtable/sharding] This enables the distribution of a database across a large number of machines, which can significantly improve performance.
[src:gcp-bigtable/sharding] In addition, if the database shard is based on some real-world segmentation of the data (e.g., European customers v.
[src:gcp-bigtable/sharding] American customers) it may be possible to infer the appropriate shard membership easily and automatically, and to query only the relevant shard.
[src:gcp-bigtable/sharding] Although it has long been implemented through manual coding (especially where rows have an obvious grouping, as in the customer region example above), this approach is often inflexible.
[src:gcp-bigtable/sharding] There is a desire to support sharding automatically, both in terms of adding code support for it, and for identifying candidates to be sharded separately.
[src:gcp-bigtable/sharding] Consistent hashing is a technique used in sharding to distribute large loads across multiple smaller services and servers.
[src:gcp-bigtable/sharding] Where distributed computing is used to separate load between multiple servers (either for performance or reliability reasons), a sharding approach may also be useful.
[src:gcp-bigtable/sharding] In the 2010s, sharding of execution capacity, as well as the more traditional sharding of data, emerged as a potential approach to address performance and scalability challenges in blockchains.
[src:gcp-bigtable/sharding] Recent academic work has proposed protocols such as Cerberus to address cross-shard atomicity by braiding consensus across multiple shards, allowing transactions to affect multiple partitions simultaneously without requiring a global lock.
[src:gcp-bigtable/sharding] Horizontal partitioning splits one or more tables by row, usually within a *single* instance of a schema and a database server.
[src:gcp-bigtable/sharding] It partitions the relevant table or tables in the same way, but does so across potentially *multiple* instances of the schema.
[src:gcp-bigtable/sharding] An advantage is that the search load for the large partitioned table can be distributed across multiple servers (logical or physical), rather than only across multiple indexes on a same logical server.
[src:gcp-bigtable/sharding] Splitting shards across multiple isolated instances requires more than simple horizontal partitioning.
[src:gcp-bigtable/sharding] The expected gains in efficiency would be reduced if querying the database required *multiple* instances to be accessed just to retrieve a simple dimension table.
[src:gcp-bigtable/sharding] Beyond partitioning, sharding therefore involves distributing large, partitionable tables across servers, while smaller tables are replicated in full on each server.
[src:gcp-bigtable/sharding] This is also why sharding is related to a shared-nothing architecture—once sharded, each shard can reside in a separate logical schema instance, physical database server, data center, or geographic region.
[src:gcp-bigtable/sharding] Sharding is intended to minimize the need for cross-shard access by partitioning data across independent shards.
[src:gcp-bigtable/sharding] This makes replication across multiple servers easier (simple horizontal partitioning does not).
[src:gcp-bigtable/sharding] It is also useful for worldwide distribution of applications, where communications links between data centers might otherwise become a bottleneck.
[src:gcp-bigtable/sharding] There is also a requirement for some notification and replication mechanism between schema instances, so that unpartitioned tables remain as closely synchronized as the application requires.
[src:gcp-bigtable/sharding] This is a complex architectural choice in sharded systems: approaches range from making these tables effectively read-only (with updates that are rare and batched), to dynamically replicated tables (at the cost of reducing some of the distribution benefits of sharding), and many options in between.
[src:gcp-bigtable/sharding] Sharding a database table before it has been optimized locally can introduce unnecessary complexity.
[src:gcp-bigtable/sharding] Sharding is generally recommended when other optimization strategies have proven insufficient.
[src:gcp-bigtable/sharding] The added complexity of database sharding can result in several potential challenges.
[src:gcp-bigtable/sharding] Richard Garriott, creator of *Ultima Online*, recalled that the term originated during the production of the game, specifically in creating a self-regulating, virtual ecology system.
[src:gcp-bigtable/sharding] Players were able to interact and harvest in-game resources via the internet, which disrupted the balance of the system.
[src:gcp-bigtable/sharding] The feature was later removed after several months of testing.
[src:gcp-bigtable/wide-column-store] A **wide-column store** (or **extensible record store**) is a type of NoSQL database.
[src:gcp-bigtable/wide-column-store] It uses tables, rows, and columns, but unlike a relational database, the names and format of the columns can vary from row to row in the same table.
[src:gcp-bigtable/wide-column-store] A wide-column store can be interpreted as a two-dimensional key–value store.
[src:gcp-bigtable/wide-column-store] Google's Bigtable is one of the prototypical examples of a wide-column store.
[src:gcp-bigtable/wide-column-store] Wide-column stores such as Bigtable and Apache Cassandra are not column stores in the original sense of the term, since their two-level structures do not use a columnar data layout.
[src:gcp-bigtable/wide-column-store] In genuine column stores, a columnar data layout is adopted such that each column is stored separately on disk.
[src:gcp-bigtable/wide-column-store] Wide-column stores do often support the notion of column families that are stored separately.
[src:gcp-bigtable/wide-column-store] However, each such column family typically contains multiple columns that are used together, similar to traditional relational database tables.
[src:gcp-bigtable/wide-column-store] Within a given column family, all data is stored in a row-by-row fashion, such that the columns for a given row are stored together, rather than each column being stored separately.
[src:gcp-bigtable/wide-column-store] Wide-column stores that support column families are also known as *column family databases*.
